[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Excellent recipe. The provider directory domain is modeled accurately (NUCC taxonomy, NPI as universal key, multi-source reconciliation challenges, CMS No Surprises Act context, network adequacy implications). The graph approach is well-justified with concrete examples that make the relational-vs-graph tradeoff viscerally clear. The writing quality is high and the voice is consistent with the cookbook's style.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The three HIGH findings are security/availability hardening issues: IAM scoping, OpenSearch access control, and a circuit breaker for the Neptune-OpenSearch coupling. None indicate fundamental design problems. The recipe's own "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section honestly identifies several of these gaps, which is good self-awareness, but the architecture should include at least the monitoring infrastructure to detect the problems it acknowledges.
